1:  Automatic summarization is the process of shortening a text document with software , in order to create a summary with the major points of the original document. 

2:  Search engines are an example; others include summarization of documents, image collections and videos. 

3:  Document summarization tries to create a representative summary or abstract of the entire document, by finding the most informative sentences, while in image summarization the system finds the most representative and important (i.e. salient) images. 

4:  There are two general approaches to automatic summarization: extraction and abstraction . 

5:  Extractive methods work by selecting a subset of existing words, phrases, or sentences in the original text to form the summary. 

6:  Research to date has focused primarily on extractive methods, which are appropriate for image collection summarization and video summarization. 

7:  Examples of this include keyphrase extraction, where the goal is to select individual words or phrases to "tag" a document, and document summarization, where the goal is to select whole sentences (without modifying them) to create a short paragraph summary. 

8:  Summarization systems are able to create both query relevant text summaries and generic machine-generated summaries depending on what the user needs. 

9:  An example of a summarization problem is document summarization, which attempts to automatically produce an abstract from a given document. 

10:  Sometimes one might be interested in generating a summary from a single source document, while others can use multiple source documents (for example, a cluster of articles on the same topic). 

11:  This problem is called multi-document summarization . 

12:  A related application is summarizing news articles. 

13:  Imagine a system, which automatically pulls together news articles on a given topic (from the web), and concisely represents the latest news as a summary. 

14:  Image collection summarization is another application example of automatic summarization. 

15:  These algorithms model notions like diversity, coverage, information and representativeness of the summary. 

16:  Some techniques and algorithms which naturally model summarization problems are TextRank and PageRank, Submodular set function , Determinantal point process , maximal marginal relevance (MMR) etc. 

17:  Keyphrases have many applications. 

18:  They can enable document browsing by providing a short summary, improve information retrieval (if documents have keyphrases assigned, a user could search by keyphrase to produce more reliable hits than a full-text search ), and be employed in generating index entries for a large text corpus. 

19:  Supervised learning approaches[ edit ] Beginning with the work of Turney, [3] many researchers have approached keyphrase extraction as a supervised machine learning problem. 

20:  Given a document, we construct an example for each unigram , bigram , and trigram found in the text (though other text units are also possible, as discussed below). 

21:  For example, if we use only unigrams, bigrams, and trigrams, then we will never be able to extract a known keyphrase containing four words. 

22:  We also need to create features that describe the examples and are informative enough to allow a learning algorithm to discriminate keyphrases from non- keyphrases. 

23:  Once examples and features are created, we need a way to learn to predict keyphrases. 

24:  In the case of Turney's GenEx algorithm, a genetic algorithm is used to learn parameters for a domain-specific keyphrase extraction algorithm. 

25:  Another keyphrase extraction algorithm is TextRank. 

26:  Instead of trying to learn explicit features that characterize keyphrases, the TextRank algorithm [4] exploits the structure of the text itself to determine keyphrases that appear "central" to the text in the same way that PageRank selects important Web pages. 

27:  For keyphrase extraction, it builds a graph using some set of text units as vertices. 

28:  For example, if we rank unigrams and find that "advanced", "natural", "language", and "processing" all get high ranks, then we would look at the original text and see that these words appear consecutively and create a final keyphrase using all four together. 

29:  Edges are created based on word co-occurrence in this application of TextRank. 

30:  For example, in a text about machine learning, the unigram "learning" might co-occur with "machine", "supervised", "un-supervised", and "semi-supervised" in four different sentences. 

31:  Running PageRank/TextRank on the graph is likely to rank "learning" highly. 

32:  This is a recall-based measure that determines how well a system-generated summary covers the content present in one or more human-generated model summaries known as references. 

33:  Recall can be computed with respect to unigram, bigram, trigram, or 4-gram matching. 

34:  Because ROUGE is based only on content overlap, it can determine if the same general concepts are discussed between an automatic summary and a reference summary, but it cannot determine if the result is coherent or the sentences flow together in a sensible manner. 

35:  First summarizes that perform adaptive summarization have been created. 

36:  Basically, if you have a collection of documents and human-generated summaries for them, you can learn features of sentences that make them good candidates for inclusion in the summary. 

37:  Features might include the position in the document (i.e., the first few sentences are probably important), the number of words in the sentence, etc. 

38:  The main difficulty in supervised extractive summarization is that the known summaries must be manually created by extracting sentences so the sentences in an original training document can be labeled as "in summary" or "not in summary". 

39:  The sentences in these summaries do not necessarily match up with sentences in the original text, so it would be difficult to assign labels to examples for training. 

40:  TextRank and LexRank[ edit ] The unsupervised approach to summarization is also quite similar in spirit to unsupervised keyphrase extraction and gets around the issue of costly training data. 

41:  Some unsupervised summarization approaches are based on finding a " centroid " sentence, which is the mean word vector of all the sentences in the document. 

42:  In both algorithms, the sentences are ranked by applying PageRank to the resulting graph. 

43:  In this case, some training documents might be needed, though the TextRank results show the additional features are not absolutely necessary. 

44:  Another important distinction is that TextRank was used for single document summarization, while LexRank has been applied to multi-document summarization. 

45:  Each article is likely to have many similar sentences, and you would only want to include distinct ideas in the summary. 

46:  To address this issue, LexRank applies a heuristic post-processing step that builds up a summary by adding sentences in rank order, but discards any sentences that are too similar to ones already placed in the summary. 

47:  These methods work based on the idea that sentences "recommend" other similar sentences to the reader. 

48:  Thus, if one sentence is very similar to many others, it will likely be a sentence of great importance. 

49:  The importance of this sentence also stems from the importance of the sentences "recommending" it. 

50:  Thus, to get ranked highly and placed in a summary, a sentence must be similar to many sentences that are in turn also similar to many other sentences. 

51:  However, the unsupervised "recommendation"-based approach applies to any domain. 

52:  Multi-document summarization[ edit ] Multi-document summarization is an automatic procedure aimed at extraction of information from multiple texts written about the same topic. 

53:  LexRank deals with diversity as a heuristic final stage using CSIS, and other systems have used similar methods, such as Maximal Marginal Relevance (MMR), [9] in trying to eliminate redundancy in information retrieval results. 

54:  The idea of a submodular set function has recently emerged as a powerful modeling tool for various summarization problems. 

55:  Submodular functions naturally model notions of coverage , information , representation and diversity . 

56:  For example, in document summarization, one would like the summary to cover all important and relevant concepts in the document. 

57:  Hence, one could combine one submodular function which models diversity, another one which models coverage and use human supervision to learn a right model of a submodular function for the problem. 

58:  Submodular functions have achieved state-of-the-art for almost all summarization problems. 

59:  Similarly, work by Lin and Bilmes, 2011, [16] shows that many existing systems for automatic summarization are instances of submodular functions. 

60:  Submodular Functions have also been used for other summarization tasks. 

61:  Specific applications of automatic summarization include: 

62:  The most common way to evaluate the informativeness of automatic summaries is to compare them with human-made model summaries. 

63:  Manual evaluation can be used, but this is both time and labor-intensive as it requires humans to read not only the summaries but also the source documents. 

64:  Similarly, for image summarization, Tschiatschek et al., developed a Visual-ROUGE score which judges the performance of algorithms for image summarization. 

65:  Domain independent summarization techniques generally apply sets of general features which can be used to identify information-rich text segments. 

66:  Recent research focus has drifted to domain-specific summarization techniques that utilize the available knowledge specific to the domain of text. 

67:  The main drawback of the evaluation systems existing so far is that we need at least one reference summary, and for some methods more than one, to be able to compare automatic summaries with models. 

